<subSubSection id="C34265476F50FF84A3C48EC9FB0EFE99" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F50FF84A3C48EC9FB0EFE99" blockId="7.[151,1436,1878,2010]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,751]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F50FF8BA3C48EC9FE95F832" bold="true" box="[199,321,1950,1975]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Shell small (up to 
<quantity id="4CA09B296F50FF8BA12F8EC9FDA4F833" box="[556,624,1950,1974]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
in length), solid and obliquely ovate. Strongly inequilateral with the umbones near the posterior end. Anterior margin long and evenly rounded, while the posterior margin is short, broadly rounded to somewhat subtruncate. Exterior surface smooth near the umbones which is gradually followed by fine commarginal growth striae, increasing in strength near the ventral margin. 
<collectingRegion id="499CF82E6F5FFF84A74789EBFB4CFF51" box="[1092,1176,188,212]" country="Oman" name="Ad Dakhiliyah" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Interior</collectingRegion>
nacreous, pallial sinus simple, ventral margin finely crenulated. Hinge line arched and consisting of chevron-shaped taxodont teeth, anterior with 6–10, and posterior with 4–5. Color white with brown periostracum on fresh specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34265476F5FFF85A3C4887FFC3DFF2A" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F5FFF84A3C4887FFC58FE02" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,751]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A3C4887FFEEFFEC5" bold="true" box="[199,315,296,320]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC94B3D6F5FFF84A2478870FDF6FEBA" author="Rehder, H. A." box="[324,546,295,319]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref59059" refString="Rehder, H. A. (1980) The marine mollusks of Easter Island (Isla de Pascua) and Sala y Gomez. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, Number 289, 167 pp." type="book" year="1980">Rehder (1980: 106)</bibRefCitation>
proposed a new species living in 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A0A8887EFC11FEC5" box="[939,965,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">EI</emphasis>
, from five worn valves collected in sand above the high tide level. He based his new species on three differentiating characters, namely a slightly larger size, a perceived lack of commarginal ridges, and number of hinge teeth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F5FFF84A3C488C3FE29FD6A" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,751]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
After studying the 
<typeStatus id="54E3886E6F5FFF84A2A488C3FDDDFE29" box="[423,521,404,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D4F6F5FFF84A13588C3FC60FE29" authority="Pilsbry, 1921" authorityName="Pilsbry" authorityYear="1921" box="[566,948,404,428]" class="Bivalvia" family="Nuculidae" genus="Nucula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nuculida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hawaiensis">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A13588C3FCDAFE29" box="[566,782,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Nucula hawaiensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC94B3D6F5FFF84A01988C3FC60FE29" author="Pilsbry, H. A." box="[794,948,404,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="296 - 326" refId="ref58418" refString="Pilsbry, H. A. (1921) Marine Mollusca of Hawaii VIII - XIII. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, 72, 296 - 326." type="journal article" year="1921">Pilsbry, 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and comparing specimens from both the Hawaiian Islands and 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A29188EEFE78FE55" box="[402,428,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">EI</emphasis>
, we came to the following conclusions: First, the size of 
<quantity id="4CA09B296F5FFF84A73488E0FB5AFE4A" box="[1079,1166,439,463]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
for the Hawaiian material, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC94B3D6F5FFF84A3C8888BFE5DFE71" author="Kay, E. A." box="[203,393,476,500]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref55643" refString="Kay, E. A. (1979) Hawaiian Marine Shells. Reef and shore fauna of Hawaii Sec. 4: Mollusca. Oahu, Hawaii (Bishop Museum Press), 653 pp." type="book" year="1979">Kay (1979: 497)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<quantity id="4CA09B296F5FFF84A2C5888BFDC9FE76" box="[454,541,476,500]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
for the 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A17B888AFD46FE71" box="[632,658,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">EI</emphasis>
material, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC94B3D6F5FFF84A005888BFC32FE71" author="Rehder, H. A." box="[774,998,476,500]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref59059" refString="Rehder, H. A. (1980) The marine mollusks of Easter Island (Isla de Pascua) and Sala y Gomez. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, Number 289, 167 pp." type="book" year="1980">Rehder (1980: 106)</bibRefCitation>
, is too close to be significant. Furthermore, none of the one hundred plus specimens collected by the senior author exceeded 
<quantity id="4CA09B296F5FFF84A76B88A8FB7FFD92" box="[1128,1195,511,535]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
.Second, not only the hinges but the dentition as well are very close. The Hawaiian specimens studied were within the range of Rehder’s species with 6–10 teeth. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC94B3D6F5FFF84A2AA8B1FFDB6FDDA" author="Kay, E. A." box="[425,610,583,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref55643" refString="Kay, E. A. (1979) Hawaiian Marine Shells. Reef and shore fauna of Hawaii Sec. 4: Mollusca. Oahu, Hawaii (Bishop Museum Press), 653 pp." type="book" year="1979">Kay (1979: 497)</bibRefCitation>
gave 10–11 teeth for adult Hawaiian specimens. Lastly, the decisive character, the lack of ventral ridges is non-existent. In well preserved 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A07B8B3AFC46FD01" box="[888,914,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">EI</emphasis>
specimens, these same ventral ridges are visible as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D4F6F5FFF84A2048BC6FE7CFD2D" authorityName="Pilsbry" authorityYear="1921" box="[263,424,656,680]" class="Bivalvia" family="Nuculidae" genus="Nucula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nuculida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hawaiensis">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A2048BC6FE7CFD2D" box="[263,424,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">N. hawaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13632A496F5FFF84A2B88BD8FDF5FD22" box="[443,545,655,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,805,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-395@8.[151,1436,805,1881]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. A–D, Nucula (Nucula) hawaiensis Pilsbry, 1921, (Easter Island); A, Exterior LV with periostracum partially present, 2.9 mm in length; B, Exterior LV, 3 mm in length; C, Interior LV, 2.8 mm in length; D, Interior RV, 2.8 mm in length; E–F, Nucula hawaiensis, (Hawaiian Islands); E, Exterior RV, 2.9 mm in length; F, Interior of same valve; G–H, Nucula hawaiensis, (Holotype, ANSP 116351); G, Exterior RV, 2.8 mm in length; H, Interior of same valve." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 2 B</figureCitation>
). Moreover, the shape is identical, the depth ranges are comparable and the general biogeography matches for 40% of all 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F5FFF84A1998BE2FD61FD49" box="[666,693,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">EI</emphasis>
bivalves. Unless strong genetic signals were to separate them, we see little reason for two species.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF2766446F5FFF84A3948E39FBC0F86F" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" startId="8.[151,250,1902,1925]" targetBox="[151,1436,805,1881]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F5FFF84A3948E39FBC0F86F" blockId="8.[151,1437,1902,2026]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
